+{
+  "contract_id": "054",
+  "feature_id": "054",
+  "name": "Work-packet template/schema alignment (NDEBT-011)",
+  "status": "approved",
+  "spec_ref": ".agent/product_spec_006.md",
+  "design_notes": {
+    "what_this_feature_is": "Phase-006 F-054: reconcile the three disagreeing work-packet surfaces NDEBT-011 flagged. templates/work-packet.template.json held {{TIER}}/{{BLAST_RADIUS}}/{{MERGE_ORDER}} placeholders in enum/integer-constrained fields, so it did NOT validate against schema/work-packet.schema.json -- while the schema's own description claimed it validated the template and both READMEs downgraded it to parse-validity-only. Fixed via Option A: the template now validates end-to-end. The three optional enum/integer dispatch fields cannot hold a {{...}} placeholder, so (after the PR #34 review) they are OMITTED from the starter template rather than shipped as literal defaults (tier-0/local/0) a copied packet could silently carry and misclassify on; they are documented in the schema for consumers that need cross-repo dispatch. Both README caveats are retired; a tools/fixtures_self_test.sh guard mechanically asserts jsonschema.validate(template, schema) in CI.",
+    "option_choice": "Option A (make the template schema-valid) over Option B (correct the schema description to name artifacts + keep parse-validity-only). Rationale: (1) the schema's PRIMARY description claims it validates the template -- Option A makes that true; (2) it enables a NON-VACUOUS mechanical assertion (jsonschema.validate) -- Option B's only assertion would be a vacuous parse-validity check; (3) precedent -- manifest.template.json already validates against its schema. The three enum/integer fields are OMITTED rather than defaulted (PR #34 review, CodeRabbit Major): they cannot carry an honest {{...}} placeholder, and a literal tier-0/local/0 would survive the consumer's {{...}}-token fill-in and silently misclassify the packet -- against the framework's mechanical-anti-silent-drift ethos. Omitting them keeps the template a minimal valid skeleton (the other optional dispatch fields keep obvious {{...}} placeholders) and defers the advanced dispatch fields to the schema, which fully documents them.",
+    "mechanical_assertion_home": "The conformance guard lives on the F-052 self-test surface (tools/fixtures_self_test.sh, a CI job), not a new validate.sh C-check. This follows the F-055 precedent (real-tree guards on that surface) and avoids the C-count blast radius (a new numbered check would touch the SUMMARY count, --help, NIZAM.json validator summary, and tools/README.md). The guard is a jsonschema.validate of the shipped template against its schema, load-bearing by construction (E03 proves a placeholder-restored copy fails it).",
+    "next_feature_decision": "After PR #33 (feature 055) merged, the next-feature AskUserQuestion has reliably aborted this session (permission stream closed, as before 050/053/055). Proceeded with 054 -- the smallest, most self-contained ungated root -- under the phase-006 standing 'proceed with the logical next steps' authorization, deliberately choosing the small feature to preserve cumulative scope-budget headroom before the larger 056; disclosed here and in the PR (the redirect mechanism). The cumulative Section-6 gate is approaching (see budget_note) and will require operator re-baseline authorization for 056/058/059.",
+    "process_honesty": "Single-session collapsed-role execution, disclosed-and-permitted by the AGF Orchestrator clause. SCOPE: 69 changed lines (ins+del) vs the 40 estimate (+73%); small in absolute terms, driven by the two governed-README version-bump + change_log entries required by C8 when reconciling their caveats. scope_over_estimate flag (not halt), well under the 3x-rolling and cumulative gates.",
+    "budget_note": "Cumulative after 054: 1763/2236 (78.8% of the 130% ceiling). The remaining ungated roots (056 est 260, 057 est 80) plus the gated 058 (est 180) and 059 (phase close) will approach or breach the ceiling, especially with typical overrun -- a Section-6 mandatory operator re-baseline decision that will surface when 056 is taken up. 054 alone (69 actual) stays comfortably clear.",
+    "review_round": "PR #34 CodeRabbit review (ASSERTIVE, CHANGES_REQUESTED, 2 findings, both addressed): (Major) 'do not ship operational fields as silent generic defaults' -- tier-0/local/0 would persist in a copied packet since the consumer workflow only replaces {{...}} tokens; resolved by omitting the three fields (the framework-aligned resolution over a doc-warning). (Minor) the NDEBT-011 resolution's 'PR #TBD' placeholder -- filled with the actual PR #34 (CodeRabbit suggested #33, but that was run_state's F-055 base-merge reference, not 054's PR). E02 re-asserts the fields are omitted; E01/E07 re-anchored to the stable phase base 15a30e1."
+  },
+  "scope": {
+    "files_create": [],
+    "files_modify": [
+      {
+        "path": "templates/work-packet.template.json",
+        "purpose": "The three optional enum/integer dispatch fields that held {{TIER}}/{{BLAST_RADIUS}}/{{MERGE_ORDER}} placeholders are omitted from the starter template -- they cannot hold a {{...}} placeholder and would silently misclassify a copied packet if shipped as literal defaults (PR #34 review) -- so the template validates end-to-end without them (they are documented in the schema for consumers that need cross-repo dispatch)."
+      },
